The answer is: 8,800

 First, we need to find Gerald's initial speed in seconds per 400-meter hurdles. Since he runs 2 seconds faster than Lee, his speed is 2 + 0.4 = 2.4 seconds per 400-meter hurdles. 

Now, we know that Gerald runs 38 seconds, so we can calculate his speed per 400-meter hurdles as follows \text{Speed per 400-meter hurdles} = \frac{38 \text{ seconds}}{400 \text{ meters}} \times 2.4 \text{ seconds/meter} 
 \text{Speed per 400-meter hurdles} = 9.6 \text{ seconds/meter} 

To find the new speed, we multiply this by 10% (or 0.1) \text{New speed} = 9.6 \text{ seconds/meter} \times 1.1 
 \text{New speed} = 10.56 \text{ seconds/meter} 

Now, we can find the time it takes for Gerald to run the 400-meter hurdles with his improved diet \text{Time} = \frac{\text{New speed}}{\text{Original speed}} \times \text{Distance} 
 \text{Time} = \frac{10.56 \text{ seconds/meter}}{2.4 \text{ seconds/meter}} \times 400 \text{ meters} 
 \text{Time} = 4.32 \text{ seconds} 

Therefore, Gerald can run the 400-meter hurdles in 4.32 seconds with his improved diet.
The answer is: 4.32 seconds

 First, we know that Freda uses 3 tomatoes per can and there are 32 ounces in one can. Since each can contains 3 tomatoes, we can calculate the total number of tomatoes used by multiplying the number of cans used by the number of tomatoes per can. 

