 First, we calculate the volume of one box \text{Volume of one box} = \text{length} \times \text{width} \times \text{height} 
 \text{Volume of one box} = 5 \text{ in} \times 6 \text{ in} \times 4 \text{ in} 
 \text{Volume of one box} = 120 \text{ in}^3 
Since there are 3 boxes, the total volume is \text{Total volume} = 3 \times \text{Volume of one box} 
 \text{Total volume} = 3 \times 120 \text{ in}^3 
 \text{Total volume} = 360 \text{ in}^3 
Therefore, the total inner volume of all 3 boxes is 360 cubic inches.
The answer is: 360 in3

 On Monday and Tuesday, Frankie watched 1-hour episodes. On Wednesday, he watched a 30-minute show. Since he watched 7 hours in total, we subtract the hours spent watching TV on Monday and Tuesday from the total hours to find the hours spent watching Wednesday's show. 
 \text{Hours spent watching Wednesday's show} = 7 \text{ hours} - 2 \text{ hours} 
 \text{Hours spent watching Wednesday's show} = 5 \text{ hours} 
Since the 30-minute shows were part of his 5-hour block, we divide the total hours by 5 to find the number of 30-minute episodes watched on Wednesday.
 \text{Number of 30-minute episodes watched on Wednesday} = \frac{5}{5} \times 0.5 \text{ hours} 
 \text{Number of 30-minute episodes watched on Wednesday} = 1 \text{ episode} 
Therefore, Frankie watched 1 30-minute episode on Wednesday.
The answer is: 1

 First, we need to find out how much water the boat took on per second. Since it took 16 seconds to row 20 feet and the boat was taking on 2 liters for every 10 feet, we can set up a proportion
 \frac{2 \text{ liters}}{10 \text{ feet}} = \frac{x}{16 \text{ seconds}} 

Solving for x gives us the rate at which the boat was taking on water per second
 x = 2 \text{ liters} \times \frac{16 \text{ seconds}}{10 \text{ feet}} 
 x = 2 \times 16 \text{ seconds} 
 x = 32 \text{ seconds} 

Now, we need to find out how much water the boat took on in 16 seconds. Since the boat was taking on 2 liters for every 10 feet, we can calculate the total amount of water taken on in 16 seconds as follows
 \text{Total water taken on} = 2 \text{ liters/foot} \times 10 \text{ feet} 
 \text{Total water taken on} = 20 \text{ liters} 

However, we also know that the boat took on 32 seconds to cover 16 seconds. This means it took on 32 seconds to cover half of the remaining distance (64 - 32 = 32 seconds). Since the boat was taking on 2 liters for every 10 feet, we can calculate the remaining water it took on as follows
 \text{Remaining water taken on} = 2 \text{ liters/foot} \times \frac{32 \text{ seconds}}{16 \text{ seconds}} 
 \text{Remaining water taken on} = 2 \text{ liters} 

So, the total water the boat took on by the time Julia reached shore is 20 liters, and the remaining water it took on is 2 liters.

The answer is: 20 liters

 First, we need to find out how many pads of paper Miguel uses in a week. Since he uses 2 pads a week, we multiply 2 by 7 to get the total number of pads used in a week. 
