 First, we need to find out how far Rosie can run in 3 hours at her initial speed of 10 miles per hour. We use the formula for distance, which is speed multiplied by time (d = rt). 

 \text{Distance in 3 hours} = 10 \text{ mph} \times 3 \text{ hours} 
 \text{Distance in 3 hours} = 30 \text{ miles} 

Next, we need to find out how far she can run at her slower speed of 5 miles per hour in 7 hours. We use the same formula again, but this time, we'll divide the total distance by her new speed (d = rt/s).

 \text{Distance in 7 hours} = \frac{30 \text{ miles}}{5 \text{ mph}} 
 \text{Distance in 7 hours} = 6 \text{ miles} 

Therefore, in 7 hours, Rosie can run 6 miles.

The answer is: 6 miles

 First, we need to find the total number of pineapples John has. Since he has 10 hectares and there are 100 pineapples per hectare, the total number of pineapples is \text{Total pineapples} = 10 \text{ ha} \times 100 \text{ pineapples/ha} 
 \text{Total pineapples} = 1000 \text{ pineapples} 
Since John harvests his pineapples every 3 months, we need to find out how many times he can harvest the total number of pineapples in a year. There are 12 months in a year, so \text{Number of harvests} = \frac{1000 \text{ pineapples}}{100 \text{ pineapples/month}} 
 \text{Number of harvests} = 10 \text{ harvests} 
Therefore, John can harvest 10 times the total number of pineapples in a year.
The answer is: 10

 First, we need to find out how far Tim can bike in one minute. Since Steve lives 3 miles away and can bike at 440 feet per minute, we can find the distance Tim can bike in one minute by dividing his speed by his distance
 \text{Distance biked in one minute} = \frac{440 \text{ ft/min}}{3 \text{ miles}} 
 \text{Distance biked in one minute} = 148 \text{ ft/min} 

Since Tim can bike 148 feet in one minute, he can cover 148/264 miles per minute. This means he can cover half of Tim's distance in one minute. To find out how long it will take him to cover the remaining distance, we divide his speed by his remaining distance
 \text{Time needed to cover the remaining distance} = \frac{2 \text{ miles}}{2 \text{ miles} - 3 \text{ miles}} 
 \text{Time needed to cover the remaining distance} = \frac{2}{-1} 
 \text{Time needed to cover the remaining distance} = 2 \text{ minutes} 

Since Steve can bike at 440 feet per minute, he will cover the remaining distance in 2/440 minutes. To convert this to hours, we divide by 60
 \text{Time needed to cover the remaining distance in hours} = \frac{2}{440} \times 60 
 \text{Time needed to cover the remaining distance in hours} = \frac{120}{220} 
 \text{Time needed to cover the remaining distance in hours} = 0.544 \text{ hours} 

Now, we add the time it takes Steve to cover his remaining distance to the time it will take Tim to cover the remaining distance
 \text{Total time needed} = \frac{2}{440} + \frac{148}{264} 
 \text{Total time needed} = \frac{2 + 148}{440} 
 \text{Total time needed} = \frac{150}{440} 
 \text{Total time needed} \approx 0.3375 \text{ hours} 

Since we cannot have a fraction of an hour, we round up to the nearest whole number. Therefore, the winner will be waiting at their house for approximately 1 hour and 20 minutes before the loser finishes the race.

The answer is: 1 hour and 20 minutes

