 First, we need to find the speed of a kangaroo. Since it takes 18 hours to travel 18 kilometers (the distance of one kangaroo's journey), we can set up the proportion
 \frac{18 \text{ km}}{3 \text{ km}} = \frac{18 \text{ hours}}{3 \text{ hours}} 

Solving for speed gives us
 \text{Speed} = \frac{18 \text{ km}}{3 \text{ km}} \times \frac{3 \text{ hours}}{3 \text{ hours}} 
 \text{Speed} = 6 \text{ km/h} 

Now, we need to find the speed of a turtle. Since a turtle travels half the speed of a kangaroo, we set up the proportion
 \frac{18 \text{ km}}{3 \text{ km}} = \frac{9 \text{ km}}{3 \text{ km}} 

Solving for speed gives us
 \text{Speed} = \frac{9 \text{ km}}{3 \text{ km}} \times \frac{3 \text{ hours}}{3 \text{ hours}} 
 \text{Speed} = 3 \text{ km/h} 

Now, we can calculate the time it takes for four turtles to travel 18 kilometers. Since each turtle travels half the speed of a kangaroo, the combined speed of all four turtles is
 \text{Combined speed} = 4 \times \frac{3}{2} \text{ km/h} 
 \text{Combined speed} = 6 \text{ km/h} 

To find the time taken, we divide the total distance by the combined speed
 \text{Time} = \frac{18 \text{ km}}{6 \text{ km/h}} 
 \text{Time} = 3 \text{ hours} 

Therefore, it will take four turtles, each traveling at half the speed of a kangaroo, 3 hours to travel 18 kilometers.

The answer is: 3 hours

