 First, we need to find the distance Alfie will fly in one day. Since he flies 400 kilometers per day, in one day, he will fly 400 * 24/7 = 96,000 kilometers. To find the number of days it takes to cover half of the circumference of the earth (40,000 km), we divide the total circumference by 2. 
 \text{Number of days} = \frac{40,000 \text{ km}}{2} 
 \text{Number of days} = 20,000 \text{ km} 
Since Alfie covers 96,000 km in one day, we can set up a proportion to find the number of days it takes to cover half the circumference. Let x be the number of days. Then, 96,000 km / x = 40,000 km. Solving for x gives us
 96,000 \text{ km} / x = 40,000 \text{ km} 
 96,000 / x = 40,000 
 x = 40,000 \times 96,000 / 96,000 
 x = 3.86 \times 10^4 \text{ km} 
 x = 3,860,000 \text{ km} 
Since we cannot have a fraction of a day, we round up to the nearest whole number. Therefore, it will take Alfie approximately 4 days to fly a distance equal to half of the way around the earth.
The answer is: 4 days

 First, we need to find the length of the tree John cut down. Since 80% of the tree is 80 feet, we can directly use this percentage to find the length of the tree John cut down. 
