 First, we need to calculate the total time Michael will spend traveling. Since he's going to Texas and Alaska, we'll consider the distance to each state separately. For Texas, the distance is 6000 km, and for Alaska, it's 2700 km (since it's closer to the equator). 

To find the total time spent traveling, we add the times for each state \text{Total Time} = \frac{\text{Distance to Texas}}{\text{Speed}} + \frac{\text{Distance to Alaska}}{\text{Speed}} 
 \text{Total Time} = \frac{6000 \text{ km}}{50 \text{ km/h}} + \frac{2700 \text{ km}}{50 \text{ km/h}} 
 \text{Total Time} = 120 \text{ hours} + 54 \text{ hours} 
 \text{Total Time} = 174 \text{ hours} 

Next, we calculate the percentage of the total distance covered \text{Percentage Covered} = \left( \frac{\text{Distance to Texas}}{\text{Total Distance}} \right) \times 100\% 
 \text{Percentage Covered} = \left( \frac{6000 \text{ km}}{6000 \text{ km}} \right) \times 100\% 
 \text{Percentage Covered} = 100\% 

Therefore, Michael has covered 100% of the total distance between Alaska and Texas.
The answer is: 100%

 First, we need to calculate the number of customers Jason needs to talk to. Since he needs to sell 15 cars and there are 25 cars available, he needs to talk to 15 / 25 = 0.6 people. However, since Jason only has 12 hours in a day, he can't talk to 0.6 people in a day. So, we need to calculate how many days Jason needs to work to talk to 0.6 people. 

To find the number of days Jason needs to work, we divide the total number of people he needs to talk to by the daily talking rate. 

 \text{Number of days} = \frac{\text{Total people to talk to}}{\text{Daily talking rate}} 
 \text{Number of days} = \frac{0.6}{12} 
 \text{Number of days} = 0.05 \text{ days} 

Since Jason works a 8 hours a day, we need to convert 0.05 days to hours. 

 \text{Hours worked} = 0.05 \text{ days} \times 8 \text{ hours/day} 
 \text{Hours worked} = 0.4 \text{ hours} 

Now, we need to calculate the total hours Jason needs to work to sell 15 cars and earn his bonus. 

 \text{Total hours needed} = \text{Number of days} \times \text{Hours worked per day} 
 \text{Total hours needed} = 0.05 \text{ days} \times 8 \text{ hours/day} 
 \text{Total hours needed} = 0.4 \text{ hours} 

Therefore, Jason needs to make 0.4 hours of telephone calls to sell 15 cars and earn his bonus.
The answer is: 0.4 hours

